<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<LinearLayout xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
    android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="match_parent"
    android:orientation="vertical">

    <!-- Phase 6.1: the host root is a BnYogaFrameLayout, NOT a stock FrameLayout.
         A stock one is not inert: every addView/setText in a batch calls
         requestLayout(), and the ensuing traversal re-measures this container and
         re-places every TOP-LEVEL node at (0, 0, hostW, hostH) — behind Yoga's
         back, in the real Activity only (never in a detached-root test), and the
         resize listener's bounds guard sees no change so nothing repairs it. Yoga
         owns ALL placement, including the top level. See BnYogaFrameLayout's KDoc. -->
    <io.blazornative.shell.BnYogaFrameLayout
        android:id="@+id/widget_root"
        android:layout_width="match_parent"
        android:layout_height="0dp"
        android:layout_weight="1"
        android:background="#FFFFFF" />

    <!-- THE [BOOT] STRIP IS A FIXED HEIGHT, NOT A WEIGHTED FRACTION — and that is
         the decision, not a detail. It used to be `0dp` + `layout_weight="2"`
         against widget_root's `3`, i.e. a flat 40% of the screen in EVERY
         orientation. A fraction is exactly the wrong unit for a debug strip: the
         panel needs a couple of lines of text, which is an ABSOLUTE amount of
         space, while the app needs everything else. Weighting it meant the strip
         grew when there was room to spare and — much worse — kept its full 40%
         when there was none.

         The failure that named this: rotate to landscape and the app's own area
         collapses from ~540dp to ~244dp on a 407 × 904dp screen, because the
         strip takes 163dp of the 407dp that is left. Content that fit in portrait
         then overflows widget_root, and since every BnYogaFrameLayout sets
         `clipChildren = false` to match iOS's `clipsToBounds == NO`
         (YogaLayout.kt), the overflow is NOT clipped — it is painted over by this
         opaque black panel, which the LinearLayout draws after it. The symptom is
         a page that just stops, with no scrollbar to explain it. (And no
         scrollbar is CORRECT: a page without a BnScroll has no scroll node, and
         the engine never invents one — the un-styled invariant.)

         Yoga is not implicated: the resize path re-solves the whole tree against
         the new bounds on any host resize (YogaLayout's addOnLayoutChangeListener
         → calculateAndApply, which re-reads root.width/height every pass). The
         space was gone before Yoga ever saw it.

         96dp holds three lines of 14sp monospace inside the 16dp padding, and it
         SCROLLS, so nothing is lost — the rest of the narration is a swipe away.
         iOS has no equivalent panel at all (the app owns the full screen there),
         so this also narrows a shell divergence rather than widening one. -->
    <ScrollView
        android:layout_width="match_parent"
        android:layout_height="96dp"
        android:background="#000000"
        android:padding="16dp">

        <TextView
            android:id="@+id/markers"
            android:layout_width="match_parent"
            android:layout_height="wrap_content"
            android:fontFamily="monospace"
            android:textColor="#00FF00"
            android:textSize="14sp"
            android:text="Booting native runtime..." />
    </ScrollView>
</LinearLayout>
